Sora R.I.P.: OpenAI's video flagship dies on April 26 — an estimated ~$1 million daily loss with declining usage was no longer sustainable.

7
00:00:47,850 --> 00:00:49,100
Story of the Week.

8
00:00:49,100 --> 00:00:55,950
Anthropic's Double Failure: 512,000 Lines of Source Code Leaked — Then the GitHub Massacre.

9
00:00:55,950 --> 00:01:06,987
512,000 lines of proprietary TypeScript code sitting publicly on GitHub — not through a hacker attack, but because Anthropic forgot to strip a source map from its build .

10
00:01:06,987 --> 00:01:14,425
The affected version: Claude Code v2.1.88, released on April 1, 2026.

11
00:01:14,425 --> 00:01:20,487
The leak exposed a 3-layer memory architecture and internal tool structures powering Claude Code .

12
00:01:20,487 --> 00:01:24,050
What followed was even more consequential than the leak itself.

13
00:01:24,050 --> 00:01:34,962
In attempting to remove the code from GitHub, Anthropic fired off DMCA takedown notices en masse — hitting thousands of completely unrelated repositories in the process .

14
00:01:34,962 --> 00:01:38,775
Developers worldwide woke up to suddenly deleted repos.

15
00:01:38,775 --> 00:01:45,237
CEO Dario Amodei publicly apologized and described the mass takedowns as "process errors" .

16
00:01:45,237 --> 00:01:50,475
Anthropic withdrew the majority of the takedowns; most repositories were restored.

17
00:01:50,475 --> 00:01:59,462
For developers and organizations using Claude Code, this incident raises three critical questions: How secure is code that runs through AI tools?

18
00:01:59,462 --> 00:02:03,287
What architectural decisions has Anthropic kept hidden until now?

19
00:02:03,287 --> 00:02:12,312
And — perhaps even more importantly — how fragile is GitHub's DMCA process when a single actor can trigger thousands of erroneous takedowns?

20
00:02:12,312 --> 00:02:20,225
"Anthropic took down thousands of GitHub repos trying to yank its leaked source code — a move the company says was an accident."

21
00:02:20,225 --> 00:02:23,575
— TechCrunch, April 1, 2026

22
00:02:23,575 --> 00:02:33,187
Open Questions: It remains unclear how sensitive the exposed architectural details actually are and whether all affected repositories have been fully restored.

23
00:02:33,187 --> 00:02:36,475
Anthropic has not yet published a technical post-mortem.

24
00:02:36,475 --> 00:02:50,387
Bottom Line: Anthropic's double failure — missing source map stripping in the build process plus mass-triggered erroneous DMCA takedowns — shows that even AI safety pioneers can stumble on basic build security practices.

25
00:02:50,387 --> 00:02:55,425
Source map stripping is no longer optional in 2026; it's mandatory.

26
00:02:55,425 --> 00:02:56,762
